<quiz>
  <question type="multichoice">
    <name>
      <text><![CDATA[Which statement best defines a]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Which statement best defines a Brønsted–Lowry acid?]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <defaultgrade>1.0000000</defaultgrade>
    <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
    <hidden>0</hidden>
    <single>true</single>
    <shuffleanswers>1</shuffleanswers>
    <answernumbering>ABCD</answernumbering>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[In the Brønsted–Lowry concept, an acid is defined by its ability to donate a proton (H⁺) to another species, forming its conjugate base.
Electron-pair donor/acceptor definitions belong to Lewis theory, and oxide-ion transfer is not the defining criterion for Brønsted–Lowry acidity.]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
    <answer fraction="100" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Proton donor]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Correct!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Electron pair donor]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Electron pair acceptor]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Oxide ion acceptor]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
  </question>
  <question type="multichoice">
    <name>
      <text><![CDATA[In the Brønsted–Lowry framework, what]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[In the Brønsted–Lowry framework, what is the conjugate base of H₂SO₄ after donating one proton?]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <defaultgrade>1.0000000</defaultgrade>
    <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
    <hidden>0</hidden>
    <single>true</single>
    <shuffleanswers>1</shuffleanswers>
    <answernumbering>ABCD</answernumbering>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[A conjugate base is formed by removal of one proton from the acid, so loss of H⁺ from H₂SO₄ gives HSO₄⁻.
SO₄²⁻ requires loss of two protons, H₃SO₄⁺ would result from proton gain, and H₂SO₃ is a different acid with different composition.]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[SO₄²⁻]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="100" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[HSO₄⁻]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Correct!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[H₃SO₄⁺]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[H₂SO₃]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
  </question>
  <question type="multichoice">
    <name>
      <text><![CDATA[Which pair represents a conjugate]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Which pair represents a conjugate acid–base pair?]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <defaultgrade>1.0000000</defaultgrade>
    <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
    <hidden>0</hidden>
    <single>true</single>
    <shuffleanswers>1</shuffleanswers>
    <answernumbering>ABCD</answernumbering>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Conjugate acid–base pairs differ by exactly one proton (H⁺), so H₃O⁺ and H₂O are conjugates.
Sets involving more than one proton difference, redox-related pairs, or unrelated acids/bases do not satisfy the conjugate-pair definition.]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
    <answer fraction="100" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[H₃O⁺ / H₂O]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Correct!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[H₂O / OH⁻ / O²⁻ (all three together)]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Na⁺ / Na]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[HCl / ClO₄⁻]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
  </question>
  <question type="multichoice">
    <name>
      <text><![CDATA[Which statement correctly describes the]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Which statement correctly describes the autoionization of water?]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <defaultgrade>1.0000000</defaultgrade>
    <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
    <hidden>0</hidden>
    <single>true</single>
    <shuffleanswers>1</shuffleanswers>
    <answernumbering>ABCD</answernumbering>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Water is amphoteric and undergoes autoionization to generate hydronium (H₃O⁺) and hydroxide (OH⁻), which underlies \(K_w\) and pH concepts.
Formation of free O²⁻ is not the normal aqueous equilibrium, amphoterism contradicts “cannot act,” and self-ionization does not require added acid.]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
    <answer fraction="100" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Water produces H₃O⁺ and OH⁻ by self-ionization.]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Correct!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Water produces H⁺ and O²⁻ in significant concentration.]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Water cannot act as an acid or base.]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Water ionizes only in the presence of a strong acid.]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
  </question>
  <question type="multichoice">
    <name>
      <text><![CDATA[At 25°C in aqueous solution]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[At 25°C in aqueous solution, which relationship is consistent with the definitions of pH, pOH, and pKw?]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <defaultgrade>1.0000000</defaultgrade>
    <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
    <hidden>0</hidden>
    <single>true</single>
    <shuffleanswers>1</shuffleanswers>
    <answernumbering>ABCD</answernumbering>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[The definitions based on water autoionization lead to the relationship pH + pOH = pKw in water (commonly pKw = 14 at 25°C).
The other expressions misuse the defined logarithmic relationships between \(K_w\), \([H^+]\), and \([OH^-]\).]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
    <answer fraction="100" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[pH + pOH = pKw]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Correct!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[pH − pOH = pKw]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[pH × pOH = pKw]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[pH + pKw = pOH]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
  </question>
