  <question type="multichoice">
    <name>
      <text><![CDATA[According to the HSAB principle]]></text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[According to the HSAB principle, which combination is generally expected to be the most stable?]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <defaultgrade>1.0000000</defaultgrade>
    <penalty>0.3333333</penalty>
    <hidden>0</hidden>
    <single>true</single>
    <shuffleanswers>1</shuffleanswers>
    <answernumbering>ABCD</answernumbering>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[HSAB states that hard–hard and soft–soft interactions are favored, so a hard acid binding to a hard base is generally more stable than hard–soft mismatches.
Hard–soft pairings are typically less favorable because hardness/softness reflects charge density and polarizability matching, which influences stability and reactivity trends.
(https://ppl-ai-file-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/web/direct-files/collection_99e4096c-742b-4ed1-9fa1-79a24cd1a07e/346f13fa-33ff-490a-9a60-0aa4e5b11115/inorganic_unit_04.txt)]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
    <answer fraction="100" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Hard acid with hard base]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Correct!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Hard acid with soft base]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Soft acid with hard base]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
    <answer fraction="0" format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[Stability is unrelated to hardness/softness]]></text>
      <feedback format="html">
        <text><![CDATA[Wrong!]]></text>
      </feedback>
    </answer>
